# =============================================================================
# Trivy ignore list for the Paperclip GreetEat deployment image
# =============================================================================
# Each entry below is a vulnerability we have explicitly reviewed and decided
# to accept for the current image build. The acceptance is conditional —
# every entry MUST have a justification line and SHOULD have a re-review
# date or a "drop when upstream fixes X" exit condition.
#
# This file is consumed automatically by aquasecurity/trivy-action when it
# scans the built image (build-image.yml).
#
# Re-review cadence: every Paperclip version bump. When a new upstream tag
# is pinned, run the build with these entries removed and see if any of
# them are no longer reachable (because upstream rebuilt the tooling layer
# with newer Go binaries). Drop the ones that have been fixed.
#
# Adding a new entry: include the CVE ID, severity, the bundled binary or
# OS package it lives in, and a one-line justification.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# golang stdlib CVEs in bundled developer tooling
# (Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode, esbuild — all installed by upstream's
# Dockerfile and shipped as compiled binaries)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These six CVEs all live in the golang stdlib that was statically linked
# into the bundled CLI binaries when upstream built them. Paperclip itself
# is Node.js — it never invokes these Go runtimes for TLS, archive parsing,
# URL handling, etc. The agent CLIs are spawned subprocesses that talk to
# their own model providers; their attack surface is the *prompts* we feed
# them, not network protocols.
#
# Drop these entries once upstream paperclipai/paperclip rebuilds the image
# tooling layer against Go ≥ 1.25.7 (which fixes the CRITICAL CVE-2025-68121).

# CRITICAL — crypto/tls: incorrect cert validation on TLS session resumption
# Reachable only via outbound TLS from the bundled Go binaries; the agent
# CLIs make outbound TLS calls to their model providers, but those endpoints
# are pinned trusted hostnames, not arbitrary user input.
CVE-2025-68121

# HIGH — archive/tar: unbounded allocation parsing GNU sparse map
# Bundled binaries don't ingest user-controlled tar archives.
CVE-2025-58183

# HIGH — net/url: memory exhaustion in query parameter parsing
# Bundled binaries don't parse URL query strings from untrusted input.
CVE-2025-61726

# HIGH — archive/zip: excessive CPU when building archive index
# Bundled binaries don't build zip archives from user-controlled input.
CVE-2025-61728

# HIGH — crypto/x509: DoS via crafted certificates
# Bundled binaries verify certs from pinned trusted endpoints, not
# untrusted CAs.
CVE-2025-61729

# HIGH — net/url: incorrect IPv6 host literal parsing
# Bundled binaries don't construct URLs from user-controlled IPv6 input.
CVE-2026-25679

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Same golang stdlib CVEs in the OLDER @esbuild+linux-x64@0.18.20 binary
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Upstream Paperclip's image ships TWO esbuild versions because different
# workspaces (server, ui, plugin-sdk) pin to different esbuild versions in
# their pnpm lockfiles. The older 0.18.20 binary was built against a much
# older Go runtime and trips a different set of CVE IDs than the newer
# 0.25.12 binary. Reachability analysis is identical: esbuild is a
# build-time bundler invoked during `pnpm build`, never at runtime, and
# its compiled-in Go binaries don't make outbound network calls or parse
# user-controlled input.
#
# Drop these once upstream pnpm-dedupes the workspaces or upgrades all
# workspaces to a single esbuild version.

# CRITICAL — net/netip: unexpected behavior from Is methods for
# IPv4-mapped IPv6 addresses
CVE-2024-24790

# HIGH — net/http, x/net/http2: rapid stream resets cause excessive work
# (HTTP/2 rapid reset, also known as CVE-2023-44487)
CVE-2023-39325

# HIGH — filepath: \??\ prefix not recognized as a Windows drive path
CVE-2023-45283

# HIGH — net/http, x/net/http2: unlimited CONTINUATION frames cause DoS
CVE-2023-45288

# HIGH — encoding/gob: Decoder.Decode panics on deeply nested structures
CVE-2024-34156

# HIGH — database/sql: Postgres Scan race condition
CVE-2025-47907

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# npm build-time / dev-time tooling vulnerabilities
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These are all in build-time or dev-server-only dependencies that the
# production Paperclip runtime never invokes. The image ships them because
# upstream Paperclip's Dockerfile installs the full pnpm dependency tree
# (devDependencies included) so that monorepo workspace builds work — not
# because Paperclip needs them at runtime.
#
# Reachability for each is "no" with the same logic: vite/rollup/esbuild
# are bundlers (build only); node-tar is consumed by package install
# tooling, not by Paperclip's storage backend (which uses the AWS SDK
# against GCS, no tar in the loop).
#
# These should be re-reviewed when upstream Paperclip bumps its dev-tooling
# pnpm versions (likely as part of the next major release).

# HIGH — rollup: RCE via path traversal during bundling
# Build-time only; rollup is not present in any code path Paperclip
# executes at runtime.
CVE-2026-27606

# HIGH — node-tar: hardlink path traversal via drive-relative linkpath
# Used by package install tooling (pnpm), not by Paperclip's storage
# backend. No code path in production extracts user-controlled tarballs.
CVE-2026-29786

# HIGH — node-tar: file overwrite via drive-relative symlink traversal
# Same reasoning as CVE-2026-29786.
CVE-2026-31802

# HIGH — vite: information disclosure via dev-server WebSocket bypass
# DEV SERVER ONLY. Production runs the prebuilt UI bundle; vite dev is
# never invoked in the deployed image.
CVE-2026-39363

# HIGH — vite: information disclosure via dev-server query parameter
# manipulation
# DEV SERVER ONLY. Same reasoning as CVE-2026-39363.
CVE-2026-39364

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Paperclip RCE — fixed in our pinned commit, NOT yet in tagged releases
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CRITICAL — GHSA-68qg-g8mg-6pr7: unauthenticated RCE via import auth
# bypass + process adapter spawn. The exploit chain (open signup -> sign in
# -> self-approve CLI auth -> import endpoint authz bypass -> spawn) is
# DOUBLY BROKEN in our deployment:
#
#   1. PAPERCLIP_AUTH_DISABLE_SIGN_UP=true is set on both the Cloud Run
#      service (compute module) and the bootstrap-ceo job (jobs module),
#      which blocks the chain at step 1 — attackers can't create the
#      account they need to get a session
#
#   2. The actual upstream fix (commit ac664df, "fix(authz): scope import,
#      approvals, activity, and heartbeat routes (#3315)") is in our pinned
#      version. Trivy can't see this because the package.json `version`
#      field still says 0.3.1 — upstream landed the code fix without
#      bumping the package version, since they haven't tagged a release
#      yet.
#
# Drop this entry when upstream tags a release that bumps @paperclipai/server
# and paperclipai package.json versions to >= 2026.410.0.
GHSA-68qg-g8mg-6pr7

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# npm runtime / build dependency CVEs — reachability analysis per entry
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Each of the entries below was triaged for reachability against Paperclip's
# actual code paths. They fall into three buckets:
#
#   - Unreachable: the vulnerable code path requires a usage pattern
#     Paperclip doesn't have (e.g. dynamic SQL identifiers, _.template
#     with user-controlled imports keys, XML parsing of user input)
#   - DoS-only and rate-limited: the issue is denial of service, not
#     code execution or data exposure, and is mitigated by Cloud Run's
#     min_instances=2 + max_instances ceiling + Google's edge rate limits
#   - Transitive and unused: the vulnerable package is a transitive
#     dependency Paperclip doesn't directly call
#
# Re-review trigger: every Paperclip version bump. When upstream rebuilds
# the lockfile with newer dependency versions, drop the entries that no
# longer match.

# HIGH — defu: prototype pollution via `__proto__` key in defaults
# Reachable only when the app merges UNTRUSTED runtime input via defu.
# Paperclip uses defu (transitively, via various config-loading libs)
# to merge static config files with hardcoded defaults — never user
# input. Unreachable.
CVE-2026-35209

# HIGH — drizzle-orm: SQL injection via improperly escaped SQL identifiers
# (also GHSA-gpj5-g38j-94v9). Reachable only when the app passes user
# input to dynamic-identifier APIs like sql.identifier() or .as(). The
# advisory explicitly states: "Applications that use only static schema
# objects, or that strictly map user input through an allowlist of known
# column or alias names, are not affected." Paperclip's Drizzle usage is
# the static-schema pattern (db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.id,
# ...))). The dynamic-identifier APIs are not used in any code path that
# accepts user input. Unreachable.
CVE-2026-39356

# HIGH — fast-xml-parser: DoS via XML
# Reachable only when the app parses XML from untrusted input. Paperclip
# uses YAML for config and JSON for the API surface; no user-facing code
# path parses XML. fast-xml-parser is a transitive dep, never called by
# Paperclip directly. Unreachable.
CVE-2026-33036

# HIGH — kysely: SQL injection via unsanitized JSON path keys
# Paperclip uses Drizzle as its ORM, NOT Kysely. Kysely is a transitive
# dependency (likely from a build-tool or dev-tool), never invoked by
# Paperclip's runtime SQL path. Unreachable.
CVE-2026-32763

# HIGH — kysely: MySQL SQL injection via insufficient backslash escaping
# Same reasoning as CVE-2026-32763 (Paperclip uses Drizzle). Additionally,
# this CVE is MySQL-specific — our deployment is on Cloud SQL for
# PostgreSQL 17. Unreachable on two independent grounds.
CVE-2026-33468

# HIGH — lodash-es: arbitrary code execution via untrusted input
# (GHSA-r5fr-rjxr-66jc). Reachable only when the app calls `_.template()`
# and passes untrusted input as `options.imports` KEY names. This is an
# extremely unusual code pattern; almost no application uses _.template
# at all in 2026, let alone with user-controlled imports keys. Paperclip
# uses Lodash for normal data manipulation (map/filter/groupBy/etc.),
# never for template compilation. Unreachable.
CVE-2026-4800

# HIGH — minimatch: DoS due to unbounded glob expansion
# DoS only. minimatch is used by glob-matching code paths inside Paperclip
# (workspace file enumeration, agent file globs). Mitigated by Cloud Run
# min_instances=2 + max_instances ceiling + Google's edge rate limits +
# the fact that glob patterns originate from operator-authored .paperclip
# yaml files, not from arbitrary network input.
CVE-2026-27903

# HIGH — minimatch: DoS via catastrophic regex backtracking
# Same reasoning as CVE-2026-27903.
CVE-2026-27904

# HIGH — multer: DoS via dropped file upload
# DoS only. Reachable on the file-upload code path (Paperclip uses multer
# for issue attachments). Mitigated by Cloud Run rate limits + Better Auth
# gating (only authenticated operators can upload), and impact is bounded
# DoS, not data exposure.
CVE-2026-2359

# HIGH — multer: DoS via malformed requests
# Same reasoning as CVE-2026-2359.
CVE-2026-3304

# HIGH — multer: DoS via malformed requests (variant)
# Same reasoning as CVE-2026-2359.
CVE-2026-3520

# HIGH — path-to-regexp: DoS via regex
# DoS only. path-to-regexp is used by Express for route pattern matching.
# Reachable only when the app constructs route patterns from user input,
# which Paperclip never does — its routes are statically defined in the
# server source.
CVE-2026-4926

# HIGH — picomatch: regex DoS in glob matching
# DoS only. Used by various glob-matching utilities. Same mitigation as
# the minimatch entries above.
CVE-2026-33671
